XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
The crash occurred on a north/south urban US Highway at an intersection with a crossing street from a shopping center that ran east/west. The northbound travel lanes for the highway were separated from the southbound lanes by a grassy median that was no less than 30 meters wide. There were four northbound travel lanes with lane one being a right turn-only lane and lane four a left turn-only lane. The crossing street had three lanes on the east side of the intersection with two lanes westbound and one lane eastbound. The two directions of travel were divided by a raised concrete island. Both roadways were straight and level and the intersection was controlled on all sides by traffic lights. The posted speed limit for the north/south highway was 72KPH/45MPH and the posted speed limit for the east/west roadway was 48KPH/30MPH. The crash occurred on a weekday in the mid-morning hours. The conditions were daylight and dry.
Vehicle 2, a 2001 Mack concrete mixer truck, was northbound in lane #2 (the right through lane), passing through the intersection on solid green when Vehicle 1, a 2001 Mazda Tribute, entered the intersection from the east (right) and collided with the right side of Vehicle 2. This caused V1 to be dragged about twenty meters north and left facing northwest in the right northbound lane. Vehicle 2 pulled forward onto the shoulder to get out of the way of traffic. Vehicle 1 was towed due to damage, and V2 was repaired on the side of the road by a company service truck, then driven away.
Vehicle 1 was driven by a 39-year old female who was not belted and whose airbags did deploy. She was transported to a local trauma center due to injury. The passenger, a 4-year old in the left rear position in a child safety seat, was coded on the police report as having possible injuries, but according to her mother in the interview, was uninjured in the crash. The Critical Pre-crash Event for Vehicle 1 was this vehicle crossing over (passing through) intersection. The Critical Reason for the Critical Pre-crash Event was coded as an unknown recognition error. During the interview, the driver maintained that she had no recollection of why she entered the intersection at all. The driver of Vehicle 1 was taking an anti-depressant for clinical depression. An illegal maneuver (failed to stop for TCD) was coded as an associated factor. No other contributing factors were known.
Vehicle 2 was driven by a 39-year old belted male who was uninjured in the crash. The Critical Pre-crash Event for V2 was other vehicle encroachment: from crossing street, across path. The Critical Reason for the Critical Pre-crash Event was not coded to this vehicle. False assumption of other road users actions was coded as an associated factor because this driver assumed that the driver of V1 would yield the right of way. The driver of V2 was taking a blood pressure medication. No other factors were coded to this driver.
